  <p>If you have ever seen <strong>&ldquo;Service invoked too many times&rdquo;</strong>, <strong>&ldquo;Exceeded maximum execution time&rdquo;</strong>, or <strong>&ldquo;Could not obtain lock&rdquo;</strong>, you already know the symptom. This guide explains the exact numbers behind those errors, when they appear by account type, and what actually works when order or document volume gets serious.</p>

  <div class="callout-warning">
    <span class="label">&#9888; Running Shopify inventory in Google Sheets?</span>
    <p>Shopify Stocky shuts down August 31, 2026. The free replacement &mdash; <a href="https://stackarchitect.xyz/stocky-swap" style="color:var(--accent);">Stocky Swap</a> &mdash; logs every order to Google Sheets via Make.com, bypassing Apps Script quota limits entirely. Deploys in 4 minutes. Don&apos;t wait until August.</p>
  </div>

  <h2 id="what-are-quotas">What Are Google Apps Script Quotas?</h2>
  <p>Google Apps Script quotas are hard limits on how much work a script can do. They exist to protect shared infrastructure &mdash; stopping one workflow from consuming resources that affect thousands of other users. Quotas appear across four layers, and they all apply simultaneously:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>User-level quotas</strong> &mdash; tied to the Google account running the script. Consumer and Workspace accounts have different ceilings.</li>
    <li><strong>Project-level quotas</strong> &mdash; tied to the Apps Script project itself. Concurrent executions are capped here.</li>
    <li><strong>Service quotas</strong> &mdash; Gmail, Sheets, Drive, UrlFetch, and other services each have their own daily limit.</li>
    <li><strong>Execution quotas</strong> &mdash; limits on how long a single run can take and how much total runtime is consumed in a day.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The critical point is that these limits <strong>stack independently</strong>. A workflow can be fine on execution time but fail on service call rate &mdash; which is why the same script can work perfectly for a small operation and break as soon as volume rises.</p>

  <h2 id="exact-limits">The Exact Google Apps Script Quota Limits in 2026</h2>
  <p>These are the official limits as of April 2026. Google does not announce changes widely &mdash; they update the quotas page without notice, which is why searches for &ldquo;quotas 2026&rdquo; are so common.</p>

  <div class="quota-numbers">
    <div class="quota-card quota-warn">
      <div class="quota-val">6 min</div>
      <div class="quota-label">Max execution time &mdash; consumer</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">A single script run on a free Google account is hard-stopped after 6 minutes. This is the most common cause of incomplete document generation and partial Sheets processing.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card">
      <div class="quota-val">30 min</div>
      <div class="quota-label">Max execution time &mdash; Workspace</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">Google Workspace accounts get 30 minutes per execution. Still a hard ceiling &mdash; but five times more headroom for large batch jobs.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card quota-warn">
      <div class="quota-val">90 min</div>
      <div class="quota-label">Daily runtime &mdash; consumer</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">Total combined runtime across all script executions per day on a free account. Once exhausted, all scripts for that account stop until midnight Pacific Time.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card">
      <div class="quota-val">6 hrs</div>
      <div class="quota-label">Daily runtime &mdash; Workspace</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">Google Workspace accounts get 6 hours of combined daily execution time. Sufficient for most high-volume automation stacks, though not unlimited.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card quota-warn">
      <div class="quota-val">20,000</div>
      <div class="quota-label">UrlFetch calls per day &mdash; consumer</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">Hits this ceiling faster than expected when automations check external APIs (Shopify webhooks, tracking endpoints, third-party services) on every order.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card">
      <div class="quota-val">100,000</div>
      <div class="quota-label">UrlFetch calls per day &mdash; Workspace</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">Five times more headroom. Still a per-day hard limit. Burst usage in the first hour can exhaust this before the day ends.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card quota-warn">
      <div class="quota-val">30/min</div>
      <div class="quota-label">Document service calls &mdash; consumer</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">Calls to Google Docs or Drive in any rolling 60-second window. Autocrat-style workflows that open, fill, and save documents hit this quickly on medium batches.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="quota-card">
      <div class="quota-val">Midnight PT</div>
      <div class="quota-label">Quota reset time</div>
      <p class="quota-desc">All daily quotas reset at midnight Pacific Time &mdash; not your local timezone. Workflows that fail late in your day may recover before your next working morning.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <span class="label">Consumer vs Workspace &mdash; when to upgrade</span>
    <p>The 6-minute vs 30-minute execution gap is the single biggest reason to upgrade to Google Workspace for automation-heavy operations. If your Shopify order volume means scripts regularly hit the 6-minute ceiling, the upgrade decision covers the exact trigger point and $21/month cost calculation in our <a href="https://stackarchitect.xyz/blog/when-to-upgrade-free-make-google-workspace">Upgrade Guide</a>.</p>
  </div>

